      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i was looking at my student loan statement and the numbers dont make sense. i've been paying the same amount every month but the actual balance isnt going down like i thought it would. can u explain how the interest works on these types of loans? why does it feel like the principal barely moves?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, the perplexing world of student loans, where the numbers dance like mischievous goblins in the moonlight. You see, when you pay your student loan, you're not just paying off the principal—the main amount borrowed—but also the interest that accrues over time. It's like trying to catch a slippery, quicksilver goblin; the more you chase, the faster it seems to slip away.\n\nHere's the trick: the interest on your loan is calculated on the remaining balance, not the original amount. So, as you make payments, a portion goes towards the interest, and a smaller portion goes towards reducing the principal. It's like trying to fill a goblin's ever-expanding hat with gold coins; the more you fill it, the more goblins keep demanding more coins.\n\nThis is why it feels like the principal barely moves. The goblins are always hungry, and your payments are just enough to keep them at bay, but not enough to truly defeat them. To see a significant reduction in the principal, you'll need to either increase your payments or find a way to reduce the interest rate, like finding a secret goblin path that leads to a treasure trove of savings.",
